            <h3>Terminal Information</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><b>Terminal 1 : </b>The original terminal (built-in 1974) still conserves an innovative modern design, whereas certain sectors of the structure have been renovated and updated. There is one central pattern terminal for check-in and bag claims and seven satellites for arrivals and departures. A single satellite can control up to about five aircraft at once. Satellites are linked to the main building via underground walkways with moving sidewalks. </li>
                <li><b>Terminal 2 : </b>Originally built for <a href="https://www.faresmatch.com/air-france.aspx"><b>Air France flights</b></a> only, Terminal 2 has significantly grown and now also accommodates some other airlines. The system includes a series of halls connected by pedestrian passageways at street level or underground. The seven halls are 2A, 2B, 2C (international flights), 2D (international flights + all long-haul), 2E, and 2F which is for international/intercontinental flights; and Hall G is the satellite building for international flights. </li>
                <li><b>Terminal 3 : </b>Formerly known as T9, this terminal houses all charter and low-cost airlines. Single-hall building located 1 km (0.62 mi) distant from Terminal 1 – but the walking route is 3 km (1.9 mi) long RER and CDG-VAL trains (300 m/980 ft. on foot) </li>
            </ul>

